    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Tonguefish are fairly-easily recognized as a group, as they have become extremely flattened and lie on their right side (not left side, as in soles) with both eyes displaced onto the left side. The pectoral fin is absent and the dorsal and anal fins join seamlessly to the anal fin, so the fish comes to a point at the posterior end.</p><p>This species has a rounded snout that is characteristically hooked over the lower jaw (creating a ‘sad-face’) and is mottled grey to brown, often with darker blotches. There are three lateral lines, one central and one close to each margin) on the upper, eyed side, but none on the underside.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_7214",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches 31 cm length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_7215",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to Namibia and South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_7216",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found to a depth of at least 110 m on sandy and muddy bottoms. As with other flatfish buries readily in the sediment with only the eyes protruding.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_7217",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Details unknown, but tonguefish typically feed on small invertebrates such as crustaceans, molluscs and worms.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_7218",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>No details available.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_7219",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Tonguefish are often confused with soles (family Solidae) but these lie on their left side with the eyes displaced to the upper or right side, retain the pectoral fin and have a distinct caudal or tail fin separate from the dorsal and anal fins.</p><p>There are several tonguefish species in the region, of which the most frequently encountered is the Redspotted tonguefish <i>C. zanzibarensis</i>. This occurs from the western Cape eastwards to Kenya and is brown with distinctive dark red to orange spots on the dorsal and anal fins.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_7220",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
